  <section class="content-section" id="section-reading-the-dictionary">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Reading the dictionary</h2>
    <p>
      Before the movement vocabulary, three things about how the dictionary
      presents tricks: the <strong>row</strong> every trick shares, the six
      <strong>browse views</strong> that regroup those rows, and the five
      <strong>kinds of object</strong> the platform keeps separate &mdash; where
      older footbag vocabularies often used one flat name for all of them.
    </p>

    <h3 class="section-heading">The trick row</h3>
    <p class="detail-muted">Every trick renders as the same two-line row in every browse view; only the grouping above it changes.</p>
    <div class="glossary-row-contract">
      <p class="glossary-row-contract-line"><span class="glossary-row-contract-label">Line 1</span> canonical trick name &middot; <code>#hashtag</code> &middot; optional <strong>&equiv;</strong> interpretation / decomposition reading &middot; optional <a href="#section-media-claim-scope">media badge</a> (<em>Tutorial / Demo available</em>)</p>
      <p class="glossary-row-contract-line"><span class="glossary-row-contract-label">Line 2</span> <strong>JOB</strong> operational notation &middot; <strong>ADD</strong> difficulty accounting</p>
    </div>
    <p class="detail-muted">
      There is no separate per-row ADD chip: the ADD magnitude is carried by the
      view's grouping header plus the line-2 <strong>ADD</strong> formula. JOB
      (<a href="#section-notation">notation</a>) and ADD
      (<a href="#section-add-accounting">accounting</a>) are the two halves of
      line 2 &mdash; both are explained in full below.
    </p>
    <p class="detail-muted">
      Two cautions about line 1. An <strong>alias</strong> (a second name for the
      same trick, e.g. ATW = around-the-world) is <em>not</em> an interpretation
      &mdash; it is the same trick under another name, with no
      <strong>&equiv;</strong> reading implied. And an interpretation is
      <em>not always settled doctrine</em>: some <strong>&equiv;</strong> readings
      are ratified structure, others are observational or depend on a curator
      ruling and may change. The <strong>&equiv;</strong> shows the reading; it
      does not promise the reading is final.
    </p>

    <h3 class="section-heading">The six browse views</h3>
    <p class="detail-muted">Same rows, six lenses. Each answers a different question.</p>
    <div class="glossary-add-weight-table-wrap">
      <table class="glossary-add-weight-table">
        <thead><tr><th>View</th><th>Groups by</th><th>Reveals</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><a href="/freestyle/tricks?view=add">By ADD</a></td><td>difficulty buckets</td><td>how layered a trick is</td></tr>
          <tr><td><a href="/freestyle/tricks?view=family">By family</a></td><td>conserved terminal mechanic</td><td>structural lineage</td></tr>
          <tr><td><a href="/freestyle/tricks?view=sets">By modifier</a></td><td>the set / body modifier used</td><td>what transforms the base</td></tr>
          <tr><td><a href="/freestyle/tricks?view=movement-system">By movement system</a></td><td>four conceptual axes (+ alternative surfaces)</td><td>the compositional system</td></tr>
          <tr><td><a href="/freestyle/tricks?view=topology">Movement Neighborhoods</a></td><td>&ldquo;feels mechanically similar&rdquo;</td><td>exploratory similarity, not a canonical taxonomy</td></tr>
          <tr><td><a href="/freestyle/tricks?view=dex-count">By dex count</a></td><td>number of dex events</td><td>mechanical complexity</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p class="detail-muted">
      The same trick appears in several of these views at once &mdash; by design,
      not duplication. One trick has a difficulty, a family, a modifier, a
      surface, and a neighborhood all at the same time, so each lens shows it
      from a different angle. The trick does not change; only the question the
      view asks does.
    </p>

    <h3 class="section-heading">Five kinds of object (and why they stay separate)</h3>
    <p>
      Older footbag vocabularies flattened families, modifiers, surfaces,
      aliases, and decompositions into one undifferentiated name-space. The
      platform keeps them separate because each is a <em>different kind of
      thing</em>, governed by different rules &mdash; conflating them is what
      makes a flat vocabulary confusing.
    </p>
    <div class="glossary-add-weight-table-wrap">
      <table class="glossary-add-weight-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Kind</th><th>What it is</th><th>Example</th><th>Where it lives</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Canonical family</td><td>a true structural lineage sharing a conserved terminal mechanic</td><td>whirl, mirage, legover</td><td>By family</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Modifier ecosystem</td><td>a system that transforms many bases; has no terminal mechanic of its own</td><td>pixie, ducking, spinning</td><td>By modifier</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Alternative surface</td><td>an unusual catch surface, not a movement lineage</td><td>sole, heel, cloud, cross-body sole</td><td>Movement system &rarr; Alternative surfaces</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Movement neighborhood</td><td>tricks that <em>feel</em> mechanically similar &mdash; an exploratory lens, not a taxonomy</td><td>Hippy downtime dex</td><td>Movement Neighborhoods</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Alias / decomposition label</td><td>another name for, or a reading of, an existing trick &mdash; descriptive, not a new trick</td><td>ATW = around-the-world; eggbeater &equiv; atomic legover</td><td>(no own view; shown on the trick)</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p class="detail-muted">
      The boundaries: a <strong>canonical family</strong> has its own terminal
      mechanic; a <strong>modifier ecosystem</strong> only transforms one; an
      <strong>alternative surface</strong> is a contact surface, not a lineage; a
      <strong>neighborhood</strong> is &ldquo;feels similar,&rdquo; not &ldquo;is
      structurally the same&rdquo;; and an <strong>interpretation reading</strong>
      (the <strong>&equiv;</strong> on line 1) describes an equivalence &mdash; it
      does not make the read-as name a productive modifier.
    </p>
    <p class="detail-muted">
      The <strong>family</strong> kind is not flat. Between a broad family and a
      one-off trick sits the <strong>productive descendant lineage</strong>
      &mdash; a named, productive cluster (such as the drifter lineage) built
      from canonical tricks but not itself a primitive family. The
      <a href="#section-families">Families</a> section maps the families and
      their lineages.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section" id="section-core-concepts">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Movement Basics</h2>
    <p>
      Welcome to the language of freestyle footbag &mdash; the words players use
      for the moves. This glossary names the surfaces you catch the bag on, the
      leg-circles and body-turns that shape a trick, and the families those
      tricks grow into. Start at the top and read down; each section builds on
      the one before.
    </p>
    <p>
      Freestyle's vocabulary is compositional: small movements combine into
      named tricks, and tricks combine into longer runs. The same trick can
      often be named at several depths &mdash; the shortest clear name is the
      one players use. For the full catalog of named tricks, see the
      <a href="/freestyle/tricks">trick dictionary</a>; for set systems as
      first-class objects (what is pixie / stepping / atomic as a system?),
      see the <a href="/freestyle/sets">Set Encyclopedia</a>; for set-notation
      reference, see <a href="/freestyle/sets/reference">/freestyle/sets/reference</a>.
    </p>
    <p class="detail-muted glossary-vocabulary-stabilization-note">
      The competitive freestyle vocabulary stabilized by roughly 2007&ndash;2008;
      no genuinely new base tricks have appeared in the corpus since. Current
      work refines and recombines rather than expands. See the
      <a href="/freestyle/history">freestyle history page</a> for the
      two-phase story.
    </p>

