      <figcaption class="glossary-timing-clock-caption" id="timing-clock-caption">
        The four-beat clock: a trick begins with a set, the bag rises through uptime, peaks at midtime, falls through downtime, and ends in a catch (stall or kick).
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <dl class="glossary-term-list">
      <dt id="term-set">Set</dt>
      <dd>The action used to position the bag before a trick. In modern usage, &ldquo;set&rdquo; refers to the uptime and midtime components together.</dd>
      <dt id="term-uptime">Uptime</dt>
      <dd>Before the peak. The bag is rising.</dd>
      <dt id="term-midtime">Midtime (hangtime)</dt>
      <dd>At the peak. The brief no-plant moment.</dd>
      <dt id="term-downtime">Downtime</dt>
      <dd>After the peak. The bag is falling toward the catch.</dd>
      <dt id="term-phases-sides">Phases and sides</dt>
      <dd>Tricks break into the three phases above by bag direction. A <strong>side modifier</strong> &mdash; same-side (<code>ss</code> / near) or opposite (<code>op</code> / far) &mdash; connects each component to its predecessor. <code>ss</code> is implied for clipper-led tricks; <code>op</code> for toe-led tricks.</dd>
      <dt id="term-attack">Attack</dt>
      <dd>How quickly a player begins the next phase's component. A transition that has to fire aggressively &mdash; like attacking the mirage quickly after the stepping set in Blur &mdash; is said to need a fast attack.</dd>
    </dl>
  </section>

  {{! ── Tier-break ruler #1 — Foundations → Families & Notation ───────── }}
  <div class="glossary-tier-break" role="separator" aria-label="End of Foundations">
    <span class="glossary-tier-break-label">End of Foundations</span>
    <p class="glossary-tier-break-note">You now have the vocabulary to read any base trick name. Below: how tricks cluster into families and how the notation system makes their composition legible.</p>
  </div>

  <section class="content-section" id="section-families">
    <h2 class="section-heading">
      Core Trick Families
      <span class="glossary-tier-badge glossary-tier-badge--intermediate">Intermediate</span>
    </h2>
    <p>
      A <strong>family</strong> is a <strong>productive movement lineage</strong>:
      a group of tricks that share a conserved <strong>terminal mechanic</strong>,
      decompose into the same skeleton, and carry a substantial set of named
      descendants the community actually reasons about. A family is not merely
      &ldquo;any trick that has spin-offs.&rdquo; Its terminal mechanic is
      <em>inherited</em> &mdash; every descendant still ends the family&rsquo;s way
      (paradox-whirl is still a whirl). Modifier and topology systems
      (paradox, symposium, spinning, ducking) are entry layers that are
      <em>used</em>, not inherited as identity &mdash; not families.
    </p>

    <h3 class="section-heading">What makes a family?</h3>
    <p>
      Whirl is the model &mdash; every whirl ends <em>leggy-in dexterity into a
      same-side cross-body clipper</em>, and dozens of tricks are built on that
      ending. Two things look like families but are not.
      <strong>Foundational surfaces</strong> (toe, clipper) are where
      <em>most</em> tricks end, so grouping by them would bury everything
      together and teach nothing &mdash; they live under
      <a href="#section-surfaces">contact surfaces</a>, not here.
      <strong>Modifier ecosystems</strong> (pixie, ducking, spinning) reshape a
      trick but have no ending of their own &mdash; they live under
      <a href="#section-modifiers">modifiers</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Structural objects sit in three tiers. A <strong>parent family</strong> is
      a top-level lineage with its own terminal mechanic &mdash; the eight
      recognized parents are mirage, illusion, butterfly, legover, pickup,
      whirl / swirl, osis, and around-the-world. A <strong>child
      sub-family</strong> folds into a parent (swirl and rev-whirl under whirl;
      torque and blender under osis). Between the two sits the
      <strong>productive descendant lineage</strong>: compositional in origin yet
      productive in its own right &mdash; the drifter lineage (a
      &ldquo;miraging clipper&rdquo; that spun off reverse-drifter and
      high-plains-drifter), barrage, paradon, flurry. The browse shows these as
      their own groups; a parent family they are not.
    </p>

    <p class="detail-muted">
      A <strong>family-anchor trick</strong> is a canonical trick that also acts
      as the productive root of a family &mdash; it has its own trick-detail page.
      Not every trick is a family anchor (flurry, witchdoctor, and paradox-mirage
      are tricks, not anchors). The cards below render anchors; the dictionary's
      <a href="/freestyle/tricks?view=family">family-view browse</a> renders every trick.
    </p>

    <p class="glossary-note">
      <strong>The family-root test is settled; fine-grained labels are still
      tidying.</strong> A public family root must clear a hard rule &mdash; more
      than two active members (&ge;3) plus a terminal identity that descendants
      inherit. Sparse two-or-fewer-member groupings below that bar are
      <strong>derivative micro-clusters (minor &amp; derived)</strong>, never
      first-class families; some legacy &ldquo;families&rdquo; are really
      <a href="#section-modifiers">modifier ecosystems</a>, surfaces, or aliases
      (see <a href="#section-reading-the-dictionary">the five kinds of object</a>).
      The root test is now fixed; the carded labels keep consolidating toward it.
    </p>

    <p class="glossary-note">
      <strong>Where the edges blur.</strong> Some groupings are pragmatic, not
      provable. The rotational cluster <strong>whirl / swirl / twirl</strong> is
      grouped together because the community reasons about them together, not
      because there is one airtight mechanic. <strong>illusion / pickup /
      legover</strong> share a leggy-over feel that resists a single boundary;
      they stay three separate parents (if a leggy super-family is ever
      recognized, it belongs on the
      <a href="/freestyle/tricks?view=topology">movement-neighborhood</a> axis,
      not as a parent-family merge).
      <strong>eclipse / butterfly-swirl</strong> and the <strong>drifter</strong>
      lineage are historical and cultural clusters as much as structural ones.
      The browse is a learning aid; some of its lines are drawn by usage and
      judgement, and a future ruling may move them &mdash; which is why some
      labels still render as their own groups.
    </p>

    <h3 class="section-heading">Parent families</h3>
    <p class="detail-muted">Top-level lineages with their own terminal mechanic. All eight recognized parents are carded here: mirage, illusion, butterfly, legover, pickup, whirl / swirl, osis, and around-the-world &mdash; though around-the-world is kept here only for structural bucketing: it is an <strong>entry-side primitive</strong> (used within tricks, not inherited as a terminal identity), so it is the one parent absent from the <a href="/freestyle/tricks?view=family">terminal-identity family view</a>.</p>
    <div class="glossary-family-card-grid" aria-label="Parent families">
      {{#each content.rootTerminalFamilies}}
      {{> glossary-family-card}}
      {{/each}}
    </div>

    <h3 class="section-heading">Descendant lineages &amp; sub-families</h3>
    <p class="detail-muted">Named compounds that descend from a parent via a chain reading. Some fold under a parent as child sub-families (swirl and rev-whirl under whirl; torque and blender under osis); others are productive descendant lineages in their own right (drifter, barrage). Their exact tier is being finalized.</p>
    <div class="glossary-family-card-grid" aria-label="Descendant lineages and sub-families">
      {{#each content.branchFamilies}}
      {{> glossary-family-card}}
      {{/each}}
    </div>

