  <section class="content-section" id="section-modifiers">
    <h2 class="section-heading">
      Modifiers &amp; Operators
      <span class="glossary-tier-badge glossary-tier-badge--intermediate">Intermediate</span>
      <a class="glossary-section-canonical-link" href="/freestyle/operators">Open standalone &rarr;</a>
    </h2>

    <p>
      Modifiers form <strong>ecosystems</strong>. A single modifier transforms
      <em>many</em> different base tricks: set ecosystems (pixie, fairy,
      stepping, quantum, atomic) reshape the entry; body / rotational ecosystems
      (ducking, gyro, spinning) reshape the midtime. An ecosystem is
      <strong>not a family</strong> &mdash; it has no terminal mechanic of its
      own; it modifies a base that does. That is why pixie appears across
      pixie-illusion, pixie-mobius, and symposium-pixie rather than as a family
      of its own. Browse a single ecosystem under
      <a href="/freestyle/tricks?view=sets">By modifier</a>.
    </p>

    <h3 class="section-heading" id="lineage-or-ecosystem">Lineage or ecosystem? A test you can apply</h3>
    <p>
      A <strong>lineage</strong> (a <a href="#section-families">family</a> or a
      descendant lineage) has an ending of its own; an <strong>ecosystem</strong>
      is a transformation you apply to someone else&rsquo;s ending. One quick
      test settles most cases: <em>can you do it on its own?</em> You can do
      &ldquo;a whirl&rdquo; or &ldquo;an osis&rdquo; &mdash; they land. You cannot
      do &ldquo;a pixie,&rdquo; only a <em>pixie-something</em> (pixie-illusion,
      pixie-mobius, symposium-pixie). The ecosystem has no landing of its own.
    </p>
    <div class="glossary-add-weight-table-wrap">
      <table class="glossary-add-weight-table">
        <thead><tr><th></th><th>Productive lineage</th><th>Modifier ecosystem</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Own terminal mechanic</td><td>yes</td><td>no</td></tr>
          <tr><td>What it contributes</td><td>a base trick to build on</td><td>a transformation of a base</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Spread</td><td>a coherent family tree</td><td>broadcast across many unrelated bases</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Example</td><td>whirl, osis</td><td>pixie, ducking, spinning</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p class="detail-muted">
      <strong>Hard cases: symposium and paradox.</strong> Both behave like
      ecosystems &mdash; they transform many bases and have no terminal mechanic
      of their own &mdash; even though older usage sometimes spoke of them as if
      they were families. The platform classifies them as ecosystems for that
      reason. That classification is curator-confirmable and may be refined, but
      the test above is what decides it: neither lands on its own.
    </p>

    {{> freestyle-modifier-reference}}
  </section>

  <section class="content-section" id="section-notation">
    <h2 class="section-heading">
      Trick Naming &amp; Notation
      <span class="glossary-tier-badge glossary-tier-badge--intermediate">Intermediate</span>
    </h2>

    {{! ── §7 mini-TOC — four arcs of the notation section ─────────────── }}
    <nav class="glossary-mini-toc" aria-label="In this section">
      <span class="glossary-mini-toc-label">In this section:</span>
      <ol class="glossary-mini-toc-list">
        <li><a href="#compositional-premise">Premise</a></li>
        <li><a href="#jobs-notation">Grammar</a></li>
        <li><a href="#notation-roles">Worked examples</a></li>
        <li><a href="#abbreviations">Abbreviations</a></li>
        <li><a href="#operational-notation">Operational reference</a></li>
      </ol>
    </nav>

    <p class="glossary-thesis">
      The language evolves by compressing recurring compositional structures
      into shorter readable symbolic forms.
    </p>

    <p class="glossary-operator-notation-framing">
      Operational notation is the compact symbolic shorthand for trick
      composition. A trick like <em>paradox</em> reads as
      <code class="notation-display-tokens"><span class="notation-token notation-surface">CLIP</span> &gt; <span class="notation-token notation-positional">OP IN</span> <span class="notation-token notation-dex">[DEX]</span></code>
      &mdash; "clipper set, then a far in-out dex." The notation lets
      readers reconstruct the body mechanics from the trick name without
      having to memorize each compound separately. For the full operational
      grammar and worked decompositions see
      <a href="/freestyle/add-analysis">ADD Accounting &amp; Analysis</a>.
    </p>

    {{! ── Compositional premise — Ben Job (1995) ───────────────────────────
        Concise primer naming Ben Job's notation contribution explicitly
        (per the codified notation-tradition exception). Frames the
        premise + 4 examples + forward-link to /freestyle/compositional-sets
        for the systematic exploration. The canonical formula itself lives
        in Generative insight below; this subsection refers there rather
        than duplicating. }}
    <h3 class="section-heading" id="compositional-premise">The compositional premise &mdash; every trick as formula (Ben Job, 1995)</h3>
    <p>
      The notation system descends from grammar work originating with
      Ben Job (footbag discussion list, 1995). Job proposed that every
      freestyle trick can be expressed as a small grammar of set-type,
      side, direction, and dexterity tokens. The base shape is documented
      formally under <a href="#generative-insight">Generative insight</a>
      below; the original article is reproduced under
      <a href="#jobs-notation">Jobs notation</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The dictionary's operational notation system descends from this
      compositional grammar, extending it with additional movement
      primitives and modifiers &mdash; swirl/twirl, body modifiers
      (ducking, diving, spinning), no-plant variants (symposium), unusual
      surfaces, and torque-class hybrids. The base grammar covers a large
      central region of the trick language; the extensions reach into the
      rest.
    </p>
    <p>
      Within that scope, many named "sets" turn out to be recognizable
      trick structures performed uptime: <em>miraging</em> reads as the
      mirage shape; <em>illusioning</em> mirrors illusion; <em>blurry</em>
      decomposes to stepping with a paradox second dex. The systematic
      exploration of these compositional relationships lives at
      <a href="/freestyle/compositional-sets">Compositional Sets</a>.
    </p>
    <p class="glossary-note">
      These are <strong>documented readings</strong>, not all settled doctrine &mdash; a
      decomposition records how a name is structurally understood today, which is not the
      same as a canonical ruling. See <a href="#tracking-vs-canonization">Tracking is not
      canonization</a>.
    </p>
    <dl class="glossary-compositional-premise-examples">
      <dt>Pixie</dt>    <dd><code>TOE &gt; SAME IN [DEX] &gt;</code></dd>
      <dt>Stepping</dt> <dd><code>CLIP &gt; OP IN [DEX] &gt;</code></dd>
      <dt>Blurry</dt>   <dd><code>CLIP &gt; OP IN [DEX] &gt; OP OUT [DEX] &gt;</code></dd>
      <dt>Mobius</dt>   <dd><code>SET &gt; (BACK) SPIN [BOD] &gt; OP CLIP [XBD] [DEL]</code></dd>
    </dl>

    {{! ── Jobs notation (historical source) ────────────────────────────────
        Dedicated reference section for Job's original 1995 notation
        proposal. The article is the gold-standard historical source for
        the grammar lineage and is archived in this project at
        exploration/fborg/JobsNotation.txt. Quoted material below is
        verbatim from that archive. Per the codified notation-tradition
        exception, naming Ben Job is permitted on this public surface. }}
    <h3 class="section-heading" id="jobs-notation">Jobs notation</h3>
    <p>
      Jobs notation refers to the original compositional grammar for
      footbag freestyle tricks proposed by Ben Job in the post
      <em>By the Way, Not the Name</em>, sent to the
      <code>footbag@footbag.org</code> discussion list on October 31, 1995.
      The article is the authoritative historical source for the grammar
      lineage and is archived in this project at
      <code>exploration/fborg/JobsNotation.txt</code>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Job's original proposal sets out the core grammar:
    </p>
    <pre class="glossary-jobs-original-formula"><code>(toe | clip) &gt;
[(same | op)(in | out) dexterity]* &gt;
(same | op)(toe | clip)</code></pre>
    <p>
      Read informally: a trick starts with a set surface (toe or clip),
      contains zero or more dex events with same/op side and in/out
      direction, and terminates with a catch surface. The original
      article notes that <em>same</em>, <em>op</em>, and <em>no plant</em>
      are all relative to the leg previously referred to.
    </p>
    <p>
      A selection of Job's original named examples:
    </p>
    <dl class="glossary-jobs-original-examples">
      <dt>Mirage</dt>           <dd><code>toe &gt; op in dex &gt; op toe</code></dd>
      <dt>Eggbeater</dt>        <dd><code>toe &gt; op out dex &gt; op out dex &gt; same toe</code></dd>
      <dt>Symposium Mirage</dt> <dd><code>toe &gt; (no plant while) &gt; op in dex &gt; op toe</code></dd>
      <dt>Symposium Whirl</dt>  <dd><code>toe &gt; (no plant while) &gt; op in dex &gt; op clip</code></dd>
      <dt>Ripwalk</dt>          <dd><code>clip &gt; op in dex &gt; op out dex &gt; op clip</code></dd>
      <dt>Double Pickup</dt>    <dd><code>clip &gt; op in dex &gt; same in dex &gt; same toe</code></dd>
    </dl>
    <p>
      The article anticipates the modifier extensions later codified by
      this dictionary &mdash; Pogo / Symposium / Spinning / Gyro,
      Stomping, Blind, hop-over, Carry (Wrap), duck, dive,
      jumping/flying, Swirl/Twirl cross-body dex, and swing (Pendulum,
      Rake) &mdash; noting that the set of primitives is finite and the
      space of tricks they generate is effectively complete.
    </p>
    <p class="text-muted">
      Source: Ben Job, <em>By the Way, Not the Name</em>, message to
      <code>footbag@footbag.org</code>, October 31, 1995.
    </p>

    {{! ── Generative Insight ───────────────────────────────────────────────
        Phase 1 of the 2026-05-21 glossary architecture overhaul. Surfaces
        the compositional-completeness framing that's implicit in the
        notation but never stated explicitly. Two paragraphs + the
        canonical structural formula. Honors the notation tradition
        without biographical attribution. }}
    <h3 class="section-heading" id="generative-insight">Generative insight</h3>
    <p>
      The notation carries a stronger claim than mere shorthand. A
      small set of primitive movement operators &mdash; a starting
      surface, a finite sequence of dex events, a terminating surface
      &mdash; generates the entire freestyle trick space combinatorially.
      The set of nameable tricks is, in principle,
      <strong>enumerable</strong>: pick a starting surface, pick a
      finite sequence of operators, read off the resulting formula.
      The community-named tricks are the formulas the community found
      worth naming. Many unnamed-but-structurally-valid tricks exist;
      naming follows usage, not exhaustive enumeration.
    </p>
    <p>
      The canonical structural form of a footbag trick is:
    </p>
    <p class="glossary-generative-formula">
      <code class="notation-display-tokens"><span class="notation-token notation-surface">(toe | clip)</span> &gt; [<span class="notation-token notation-positional">(same | op)</span> <span class="notation-token notation-positional">(in | out)</span> <span class="notation-token notation-dex">dexterity</span>]<sup>*</sup> &gt; <span class="notation-token notation-positional">(same | op)</span> <span class="notation-token notation-surface">(toe | clip)</span></code>
    </p>
    <p>
      A surface kick or stall opens the trick; zero or more dex events
      compose the middle; a surface kick or stall closes it. The
      <code>*</code> marks the iterable interior &mdash; one dex
      produces a simple compound, two produces a deeper one,
      three-and-up produces the named families
      (<em>blurry</em>, <em>barraging</em>, <em>flurry</em>) that
      compress longer chains under a single folk name. The trick
      dictionary is a <em>curated subset</em> of this formula's
      generative output, not its full closure. Modifiers (paradox,
      symposium, spinning, ducking) modulate the
      <code>(same | op)(in | out)</code> choices and the body
      configuration during the dex events; their effects layer onto
      the same generative skeleton.
    </p>

    {{! ── Glyph quick-reference ──────────────────────────────────────────
        Visible-symbol strip at the top of §7 so the section opens with
        concrete glyphs rather than prose. Data sourced from
        content.operatorBoard.tiers; tier colors match the shared
        operator-board partial's tier palette. }}
    <div class="glossary-glyph-quickref" aria-label="Operator glyph quick reference">
      {{#each content.operatorBoard.tiers}}
      <div class="glossary-glyph-quickref-tier glossary-glyph-quickref-tier--{{key}}">
        <span class="glossary-glyph-quickref-tier-label">{{title}}</span>
        <ul class="glossary-glyph-quickref-list">
          {{#each operators}}
          <li class="glossary-glyph-quickref-cell">
            <span class="glossary-glyph-quickref-glyph">{{glyph}}</span>
            <span class="glossary-glyph-quickref-name">{{name}}</span>
          </li>
          {{/each}}
        </ul>
      </div>
      {{/each}}
    </div>

    {{! Notation in practice — three compact symbol-first examples.
        Static content; opens §7 with concrete tokenized formulas before
        the prose explainer. }}
    <div class="glossary-notation-in-practice" aria-label="Notation in practice — three compact examples">
      <p class="glossary-notation-row">
        <span class="glossary-notation-label">single base anchor</span>
        <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation"><span class="notation-token notation-core-family">whirl</span></code>
      </p>
      <p class="glossary-notation-row">
        <span class="glossary-notation-label">modifier + base</span>
        <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation"><span class="notation-token notation-modifier">paradox</span> <span class="notation-token notation-core-family">whirl</span></code>
      </p>
      <p class="glossary-notation-row">
        <span class="glossary-notation-label">deep compound</span>
        <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation"><span class="notation-token notation-modifier">stepping</span> <span class="notation-token notation-modifier">ducking</span> <span class="notation-token notation-modifier">paradox</span> <span class="notation-token notation-core-family">torque</span></code>
        <span class="glossary-notation-shorthand">&equiv; <strong>gauntlet</strong> (7 ADD)</span>
      </p>
    </div>

    <p>
      The longer you stack operators on a base, the longer the name &mdash;
      until the community converges on a shorter shorthand. Jobs notation
      is that shorthand made legible. A trick called &ldquo;<a href="/freestyle/tricks/mobius">mobius</a>&rdquo;
      decompresses to &ldquo;spinning ss torque&rdquo;, and further to
      &ldquo;spinning ss miraging osis&rdquo;. All three forms are
      legitimate; the community uses the shortest readable one. See the
      <a href="#symbolic-compression-flow">symbolic-compression flow</a>
      for a worked example.
    </p>
    {{! Operator → named-compound block. Five compact compositions, all
        visible-token, demonstrate how operators stacked on bases produce
        the named tricks that appear in the dictionary. }}
    <p>Notation makes composition visible. Operator + base &rarr; named compound:</p>
    <div class="glossary-notation-mappings" aria-label="Operator → named compound mappings">
      <p class="glossary-notation-row">
        <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation"><span class="notation-token notation-set">pixie</span> + <span class="notation-token notation-core-family">butterfly</span></code>
        <span class="glossary-notation-shorthand">&rarr; <strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/dimwalk">DIMWALK</a></strong></span>
      </p>
      <p class="glossary-notation-row">
        <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation"><span class="notation-token notation-modifier">stepping</span> + <span class="notation-token notation-core-family">butterfly</span></code>
        <span class="glossary-notation-shorthand">&rarr; <strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/ripwalk">RIPWALK</a></strong></span>
      </p>
      <p class="glossary-notation-row">
        <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation"><span class="notation-token notation-modifier">paradox</span> + <span class="notation-token notation-core-family">whirl</span></code>
        <span class="glossary-notation-shorthand">&rarr; <strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/paradox-whirl">PARADOX WHIRL</a></strong></span>
      </p>
      <p class="glossary-notation-row">
        <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation"><span class="notation-token notation-set">pixie</span> + <span class="notation-token notation-modifier">ducking</span> + <span class="notation-token notation-core-family">butterfly</span></code>
        <span class="glossary-notation-shorthand">&rarr; <strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/phoenix">PHOENIX</a></strong></span>
      </p>
      <p class="glossary-notation-row">
        <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation"><span class="notation-token notation-modifier">spinning</span> + <span class="notation-token notation-core-family">torque</span></code>
        <span class="glossary-notation-shorthand">&rarr; <strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/mobius">MOBIUS</a></strong></span>
      </p>
    </div>

    <h3>A beginner example: <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation">{{#with content.notationExamples.whirl}}{{#each tokens}}<span class="notation-token notation-{{cssRole}}" data-role="{{role}}" title="{{label}}">{{text}}</span>{{#unless @last}} {{/unless}}{{/each}}{{/with}}</code></h3>
    <p>
      A trick whose notation is just <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation">{{#with content.notationExamples.whirl}}{{#each tokens}}<span class="notation-token notation-{{cssRole}}" data-role="{{role}}" title="{{label}}">{{text}}</span>{{/each}}{{/with}}</code>
      is itself the family anchor. It carries one body rotation and resolves
      at its catch &mdash; no modifiers stacked on, no set primitive prefacing it.
      A single token tells you: this is the structural root.
    </p>

    <h3>A compound example: <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation">{{#with content.notationExamples.paradoxWhirl}}{{#each tokens}}<span class="notation-token notation-{{cssRole}}" data-role="{{role}}" title="{{label}}">{{text}}</span>{{#unless @last}} {{/unless}}{{/each}}{{/with}}</code></h3>
    <p>
      The paradox modifier on a whirl base. The modifier (yellow-olive)
      shapes the body position; the base anchor (green) carries the
      rotation and family identity. +1 ADD on top of whirl.
    </p>

    <h3>A modifier-heavy example: <code class="notation-display-tokens glossary-inline-notation">{{#with content.notationExamples.gauntlet}}{{#each tokens}}<span class="notation-token notation-{{cssRole}}" data-role="{{role}}" title="{{label}}">{{text}}</span>{{#unless @last}} {{/unless}}{{/each}}{{/with}}</code></h3>
    <p>
      Three body modifiers stacked on a torque base; the community calls
      it Gauntlet, 7 ADD. Each modifier contributes its own +1 above the
      base.
    </p>

    <h3 id="notation-roles">Color-coded structural roles</h3>
    <p>
      The visual hierarchy is restrained &mdash; only the four primary roles
      (core family, set, rotation, body modifier) carry color saturation.
      Hover any token on a trick page to see its role and resolved family name.
    </p>

    <h3 id="abbreviations">Abbreviations</h3>
    <p>Shorthand commonly seen in trick names and in operational notation. The two lists below separate the two contexts; a few abbreviations appear in both, listed under their primary domain.</p>

    <h4>Trick-name shorthand</h4>
    <p class="freestyle-section-sub">The shorthand that appears in trick titles and composition prose.</p>
    <div class="moves-table-wrap">
      <table class="moves-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Abbreviation</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {{#each content.abbreviations.trickNames}}
          <tr><td><code>{{short}}</code></td><td>{{meaning}}</td></tr>
          {{/each}}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h4>Operational-notation tokens</h4>
    <p class="freestyle-section-sub">The bracket-flagged component tokens that appear inside operational notation strings.</p>
    <div class="moves-table-wrap">
      <table class="moves-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Abbreviation</th><th>Meaning</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {{#each content.abbreviations.operationalTokens}}
          <tr><td><code>{{short}}</code></td><td>{{meaning}}</td></tr>
          {{/each}}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    {{! ── Operational notation: advanced subsection ───────────────────────
        Reference for the bracket-flag operational notation token vocabulary.
        Collapsed by default (Phase 1) so §7 reads primer-first; direct
        navigation to #operational-notation or any #op-* child anchor
        auto-opens the details element. }}
    <details class="glossary-operational-details" id="operational-notation">
      <summary class="glossary-operational-details-summary">
        <span class="glossary-operational-details-title">Operational notation</span>
        <span class="glossary-tier-badge glossary-tier-badge--advanced">Advanced Reference</span>
        <span class="glossary-operational-details-hint">Bracket-flag token vocabulary &mdash; click to expand</span>
      </summary>

    <table class="glossary-layer-contrast">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Layer</th><th>Describes</th><th>Renders as</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Semantic</strong></td>
          <td>Compositional structure &mdash; what the trick <em>is</em></td>
          <td>Operator stack (e.g., <code>stepping ducking paradox torque</code>)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Operational</strong></td>
          <td>Execution mechanics &mdash; what the body <em>does</em></td>
          <td>Bracket-flagged sequence (e.g., <code>CLIP &gt; OP IN [DEX] &gt; OP OUT [DEX] &gt; [DEL] CLIP</code>)</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>
      The two layers are complementary, not interchangeable. The same trick
      may be named at several semantic stopping depths yet still have a
      single canonical operational form. Trick-detail pages render both
      side-by-side when both are authored.
    </p>
    <p class="detail-muted">
      Operational notation lives behind the &ldquo;Set notation (operational)&rdquo; section on per-trick pages. The reference below is the token vocabulary for that surface.
    </p>

    <h4>Component flags</h4>
    <p>Square-bracket annotations on a move that mark which structural component is in play. Multiple flags may stack on a single move.</p>
    <dl class="operational-glossary">
      <dt id="op-flag-dex"><code>[DEX]</code></dt>
      <dd>Dexterity component &mdash; the move involves bag-foot interaction (the foot circles around or contacts the bag).</dd>
      <dt id="op-flag-del"><code>[DEL]</code></dt>
      <dd>Delay component &mdash; the move ends in a stall on a foot or surface. Typically the final segment of an operational notation string.</dd>
      <dt id="op-flag-bod"><code>[BOD]</code></dt>
      <dd>Body-position component &mdash; the move includes a body pose change (spin, duck, dive, paradox).</dd>
      <dt id="op-flag-xbd"><code>[XBD]</code></dt>
      <dd>Cross-body component &mdash; the delay or move sits on the opposite-side surface from the plant foot. Typically appears with <code>[DEL]</code> on the landing.</dd>
      <dt id="op-flag-pdx"><code>[PDX]</code></dt>
      <dd>Paradox component &mdash; flags a cross-body far dex requiring a hip-pivot repositioning to bring the leg under the bag. Operationally: <code>CLIP &gt; OP IN [DEX]</code> (clipper set, far in-out dex). Equivalent to the <code>paradox</code> body modifier in semantic notation.</dd>
      <dt id="op-flag-xdex"><code>[XDEX]</code></dt>
      <dd>X-Dex component &mdash; a full-circle dex variant. In canonical usage, X-Dex applies only to specific named tricks; some external references use the flag more broadly.</dd>
    </dl>

    <h4>Sides</h4>
    <p>The side prefix on a move tells you which leg performs it relative to the plant foot.</p>
    <dl class="operational-glossary">
      <dt id="op-side-same"><code>SAME</code></dt>
      <dd>Same side as the plant foot. Roughly equivalent to the <code>SS</code> abbreviation seen in some trick names.</dd>
      <dt id="op-side-op"><code>OP</code></dt>
      <dd>Opposite side from the plant foot. The non-plant leg performs the move.</dd>
    </dl>

    <h4>Directions</h4>
    <p>The arc-direction tokens describe the bag's path during the dex.</p>
    <dl class="operational-glossary">
      <dt id="op-direction-in"><code>IN</code></dt>
      <dd>Inward arc &mdash; the bag travels toward the body.</dd>
      <dt id="op-direction-out"><code>OUT</code></dt>
      <dd>Outward arc &mdash; the bag travels away from the body.</dd>
      <dt id="op-direction-front"><code>FRONT</code> / <code>BACK</code></dt>
      <dd>
        Forward / backward direction. Standalone <code>FRONT</code> or
        <code>BACK</code> describes the arc; when followed by
        <code>WHIRL</code> or <code>SWIRL</code>, the two tokens fuse
        into a single rotational-variant move (e.g.
        <code>FRONT WHIRL</code>, <code>BACK SWIRL</code>).
      </dd>
    </dl>

    <h4 id="op-sequence-operators">Sequence operators</h4>
    <p>The arrow tokens segment the operational notation into discrete sub-actions.</p>
    <dl class="operational-glossary">
      <dt id="op-seq-minor"><code>&gt;</code></dt>
      <dd>Sub-step boundary &mdash; continuous flow within a beat group. The next move follows directly from the previous one without major pause or replant.</dd>
      <dt id="op-seq-major"><code>&gt;&gt;</code></dt>
      <dd>Major step boundary &mdash; often signals a no-plant break, a beat change, or a body-action transition. Visually heavier than <code>&gt;</code>; typically pairs with <code>(no plant while)</code> on a following move.</dd>
    </dl>

    <h4 id="op-pre-states">Pre-move state flags</h4>
    <p>Lowercase parenthesized annotations that describe the body state during the next move.</p>
    <dl class="operational-glossary">
      <dt id="op-prestate-back"><code>(back)</code> / <code>(front)</code></dt>
      <dd>Backward / forward direction of the next body action. Most often seen with <code>SPIN</code>: <code>(back) SPIN [BOD]</code> = backward body spin.</dd>
      <dt id="op-prestate-no-plant"><code>(no plant while)</code></dt>
      <dd>The support leg does not plant during this segment. Common in dense compounds where the body is mid-air during the move.</dd>
      <dt id="op-prestate-rooted"><code>(rooted)</code></dt>
      <dd>Held / rooted position; no plant. Corresponds to the <code>rooted</code> set primitive in the modifier table.</dd>
    </dl>

    <h4 id="op-surfaces">Surfaces &amp; body actions (reference)</h4>
    <p>The remaining vocabulary is small enough to list verbatim:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><code>CLIP</code>, <code>TOE</code> &mdash; plant or landing surfaces</li>
      <li><code>SPIN</code>, <code>DUCK</code>, <code>DIVE</code> &mdash; body actions</li>
      <li><code>FRONT WHIRL</code> / <code>BACK WHIRL</code> / <code>FRONT SWIRL</code> / <code>BACK SWIRL</code> &mdash; rotational dex variants on a rotational base</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="detail-muted">
      For the broader set notation reference (set primitives like Pixie,
      Fairy, Atomic, Quantum and how they decompose), see
      <a href="/freestyle/sets/reference">Set notation reference</a>.
    </p>
    </details>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section" id="section-add-accounting">
    <h2 class="section-heading" id="traditional-reference">
      ADD Accounting
      <span class="glossary-tier-badge glossary-tier-badge--intermediate">Intermediate</span>
    </h2>

    <h3 id="run-quality">ADD philosophy</h3>
    <p>
      <strong>ADD (Additional Degree of Difficulty)</strong> is
      <em>additive structural accounting</em>: each base trick has a weight,
      each modifier has a weight, and a trick's total is the sum. Each ATAM
      bracket-flag (<code>[BOD]</code> / <code>[DEX]</code> /
      <code>[XBD]</code> / <code>[DEL]</code> / <code>[UNS]</code>) in the
      operational notation contributes 1 ADD; modifier stacks accumulate
      above the base trick value. The same logic lets the dictionary read
      <em><a href="/freestyle/tricks/mobius">mobius</a></em> as &ldquo;gyro torque&rdquo; and arrive at the same
      ADD math either way.
    </p>

    <h3>Base trick weights</h3>
    <p>
      The twelve canonical atoms each have a fixed ADD value; modifier
      stacks compose onto them.
    </p>
    <div class="glossary-add-weight-table-wrap">
      <table class="glossary-add-weight-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Atom</th><th>ADD</th><th>Role</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>toe-stall</td><td>1</td><td>foundational delay</td></tr>
          <tr><td>clipper-stall</td><td>2</td><td>cross-body delay</td></tr>
          <tr><td>around-the-world</td><td>2</td><td>1-dex atom</td></tr>
          <tr><td>orbit</td><td>2</td><td>reverse ATW</td></tr>
          <tr><td>legover</td><td>1</td><td>1-dex toe terminal</td></tr>
          <tr><td>pickup</td><td>1</td><td>reverse legover</td></tr>
          <tr><td>mirage</td><td>2</td><td>dex-anchored entry topology</td></tr>
          <tr><td>illusion</td><td>2</td><td>reverse mirage</td></tr>
          <tr><td>butterfly</td><td>3</td><td>dex+xbody+stall</td></tr>
          <tr><td>osis</td><td>3</td><td>body+xbody+stall</td></tr>
          <tr><td>whirl</td><td>3</td><td>dex+xbody+stall</td></tr>
          <tr><td>swirl</td><td>3</td><td>swirl+xbody+stall</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3>Modifier weights</h3>
    <p>
      Two columns: the non-rotational bonus on most bases, the rotational
      bonus on rotational atoms (whirl / mirage / torque / blender / swirl /
      drifter / osis / illusion). Atomic, furious, and nuclear add extra
      weight on rotational bases.
    </p>
    <div class="glossary-add-weight-table-wrap">
      <table class="glossary-add-weight-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Modifier</th><th>Non-rotational</th><th>Rotational</th><th>Class</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>paradox</td><td>+1</td><td>+1</td><td>body</td></tr>
          <tr><td>stepping</td><td>+1</td><td>+1</td><td>body</td></tr>
          <tr><td>ducking</td><td>+1</td><td>+1</td><td>body</td></tr>
          <tr><td>symposium</td><td>+1</td><td>+1</td><td>body (no-plant)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>spinning</td><td>+1</td><td>+1</td><td>body (rotation)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>whirling</td><td>+1</td><td>+1</td><td>body</td></tr>
          <tr><td>atomic</td><td>+1</td><td>+2</td><td>set</td></tr>
          <tr><td>furious</td><td>+2</td><td>+2</td><td>set (two-dex ≡ barraging)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>nuclear</td><td>+2</td><td>+2</td><td>set (composite ≡ paradox+illusion)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>blurry</td><td>+1</td><td>+1</td><td>set (composite ≡ stepping+paradox)</td></tr>
          <tr><td>pixie</td><td>+1</td><td>+1</td><td>set</td></tr>
          <tr><td>fairy</td><td>+1</td><td>+1</td><td>set</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h3>Additive formulas</h3>
    <p>
      ADD = base + modifier stack. Example:
      <code>paradox(+1) + mirage(2) = 3 ADD</code>. The operational
      notation chain mirrors the formula's term order.
    </p>

    <h3>Complementary formulas</h3>
    <p>
      Some compound modifier labels are folk shorthand for two-operator
      stacks. <em>Blurry</em> is the canonical example:
      <code>blurry = stepping + paradox</code>. Composite labels like this are
      decomposed into their underlying operators so the additive math surfaces
      at the atom level (see <a href="/freestyle/tricks/blur">Blur</a> below).
    </p>

    <h3>Decomposition chains</h3>
    <p>
      Multi-modifier compounds derive ADD by walking the chain outward
      from the base. <em>Stepping paradox whirl</em> =
      <code>stepping(+1) + paradox(+1) + whirl(3) = 5 ADD</code>. The
      same chain doubles as the trick's compositional reading on its
      detail page.
    </p>

    <h3>Worked examples</h3>
    <p>
      Five examples cover the additive pattern, composite-modifier
      shorthand, and currently-open doctrine cases. Each card shows
      compact notation, official ADD, and derivation; commentary
      collapses behind the card title.
    </p>
    <div class="glossary-add-examples-grid">
      {{#each content.addWorkedExamples}}
      <article class="glossary-add-example-card" id="add-example-{{slug}}">
        <header class="glossary-add-example-head">
          <h4 class="glossary-add-example-title">{{displayName}}</h4>
          <span class="glossary-add-example-status glossary-add-example-status--{{status}}">
            {{#if (eq status 'canonical')}}canonical{{/if}}
            {{#if (eq status 'pending-doctrine')}}pending doctrine{{/if}}
            {{#if (eq status 'doctrine-locked')}}doctrine-locked{{/if}}
          </span>
        </header>
        <dl class="glossary-add-example-fields">
          <dt>Compact</dt>
          <dd>{{compactNotation}}</dd>
          <dt>Official ADD</dt>
          <dd class="glossary-add-example-add">{{officialAdd}}</dd>
          <dt>Derivation</dt>
          <dd><code>{{derivation}}</code></dd>
        </dl>
        {{#if observationalNote}}
        <details class="glossary-family-card-observational">
          <summary class="glossary-family-card-observational-summary">
            <span class="glossary-family-card-observational-title">Why it matters</span>
            <span class="glossary-layer-badge glossary-layer-badge--observational">observational</span>
          </summary>
          <p class="glossary-family-card-observational-body">{{observationalNote}}</p>
        </details>
        {{/if}}
      </article>
      {{/each}}
    </div>

    <details class="glossary-family-card-observational">
      <summary class="glossary-family-card-observational-summary">
        <span class="glossary-family-card-observational-title">Discrepancy cases &amp; policy-dependent semantics</span>
        <span class="glossary-layer-badge glossary-layer-badge--advanced">advanced</span>
      </summary>
      <p class="glossary-family-card-observational-body">
        Some compounds show a gap between the naïvely computed ADD and the
        official value (mobius, sumo). These are settled cases where the
        mechanism is known &mdash; mobius via rotational-frame continuity, sumo
        via an X-Dex on the following dex &mdash; and trick-detail pages render
        the official value with the divergence noted. The counting-frame
        doctrine (whether [PDX] is independently flag-counted vs absorbed
        into the dex flag) is the main remaining source of multi-source
        disagreement; see <a href="/freestyle/add-analysis">ADD Accounting &amp;
        Analysis</a> for case-by-case adjudication.
      </p>
    </details>

    <details class="glossary-details">
      <summary>
        <span class="glossary-layer-badge glossary-layer-badge--advanced">[advanced]</span>
        Multi-bag governing rule (boundary doctrine)
      </summary>
      <p>
        Multi-bag freestyle (controlling more than one bag at a time) is a
        boundary object relative to the single-bag freestyle dictionary that
        the rest of this glossary describes. The platform's governing rule
        for multi-bag ADD accounting is: <strong>one additional ADD for each
        simultaneously controlled bag</strong>. Two-bag juggling reads as
        <code>TOE &gt; TOE</code> with <code>delay(2) = 2 ADD</code>; three-bag
        juggling reads as <code>TOE &gt; TOE &gt; TOE</code> with
        <code>delay(3) = 3 ADD</code>; and so on. Each simultaneously
        controlled bag contributes one delay ADD.
      </p>
      <p>
        Multi-bag rows currently sit under <code>category=multi-bag</code> and
        ontology status "boundary object" pending a future dedicated
        multi-bag freestyle module. The single-bag dictionary axes (family,
        movement system, topology, sets) do not classify multi-bag rows.
      </p>
    </details>

    <details class="glossary-details">
      <summary>
        <span class="glossary-layer-badge glossary-layer-badge--advanced">[advanced]</span>
        ADD value can flatten execution difficulty
      </summary>
      <p>
        Some historically assigned ADD values flatten major differences in
        execution difficulty or athletic demand. The clearest example sits at
        the 2 ADD layer: hop-over, walk-over, and wrap are all historically
        classified as 2-ADD moves despite substantial differences in balance,
        timing, mobility, and aerial coordination. Hop-over carries a body
        jump over a held delay (mid-air clearance, single landing leg);
        walk-over passes the opposite leg over a grounded delay (balance, not
        jump); wrap pulls the bag around the support leg into a cross-body
        position (no body event at all). The three share the held-delay
        leg-over chassis but otherwise have very different physical demands.
      </p>
      <p>
        The platform preserves historical ADD doctrine (the published value
        stays canonical) while allowing structural and mechanical relationships
        to be discussed separately on the per-trick detail pages and via the
        movement-system, family, and topology browse axes. The same pattern
        recurs at other ADD layers (1-ADD body kicks vs anatomical stalls;
        3-ADD compounds whose execution difficulty diverges from their flat
        ADD-arithmetic). ADD is one axis of difficulty, not all of it.
      </p>
    </details>

    <p class="glossary-cross-link">
      For the full mechanical walkthrough with all resolved-formula sprints,
      see <a href="/freestyle/add-analysis">ADD Accounting &amp; Analysis</a>.
      For run-quality tiers (Tiltless, Guiltless, Tripless, Fearless,
      Beastly, Godly, Genuine, BOP) and competitive formats (Sick3,
      Shred:30, Circle), see
      <a href="/freestyle/combo-analysis">Combo Analysis</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  {{! ── Tier-break ruler #2 — Notation/ADD → Composition & the system ── }}
  <div class="glossary-tier-break" role="separator" aria-label="End of Notation and Accounting">
    <span class="glossary-tier-break-label">End of Notation &amp; Accounting</span>
    <p class="glossary-tier-break-note">You can now read trick-detail pages and follow a decomposition chain end-to-end. Below: how tricks combine into longer sequences, and the system-level view of how the vocabulary fits together.</p>
  </div>

  <section class="content-section" id="section-composition">
    <h2 class="section-heading">
      Symbolic Composition
      <span class="glossary-tier-badge glossary-tier-badge--intermediate">Intermediate</span>
    </h2>
    <p>
      Above the single-trick level, tricks combine into longer sequences. The
      vocabulary below describes how tricks are <em>used</em>, not how they
      are defined.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Run</strong>: a continuous sequence of tricks.</li>
      <li><strong>Shuffle</strong>: alternating sides rhythmically.</li>
      <li><strong>Link / Transition</strong>: the connection between tricks.</li>
      <li><strong>Connector Trick</strong>: a trick commonly used to maintain flow. Whirl-family tricks often act as connectors.</li>
      <li><strong>Dropless</strong>: a run without drops.</li>
      <li><strong>Density</strong>: average ADD per trick in a run.</li>
      <li><strong>Shred Circle</strong>: a group format where players take turns performing runs.</li>
    </ul>

    {{! ── Derivation atlas — five compositional examples. Relocated here
        (Phase E) from the glossary opening: it belongs after the reader
        knows families, modifiers, notation, and ADD. The `derivation-atlas`
        anchor is preserved for inbound deep-links. }}
    <h3 class="section-heading glossary-derivation-atlas-heading" id="derivation-atlas">
      Derivation atlas &mdash; five compositional examples
    </h3>
    <p class="glossary-derivation-atlas-intro">
      Five entries demonstrating the compositional system in one place: a
      root family (<a href="/freestyle/tricks/whirl">whirl</a>), a modifier (<a href="/freestyle/tricks/paradox">paradox</a>), a compound trick (<a href="/freestyle/tricks/flurry">flurry</a>),
      a symbolic-compression bridge (<a href="/freestyle/tricks/blur">blur</a>), and a rotational-doctrine
      worked example (<a href="/freestyle/tricks/mobius">mobius</a>). Each panel stacks five axes &mdash; formula,
      family, ADD with breakdown, lineage, and shorthand &mdash; so they
      read as one object.
    </p>
    <div class="glossary-derivation-atlas">
      {{#each content.derivationAtlas}}
        {{> derivation-panel entry=this}}
      {{/each}}
    </div>

    {{! ── Vocabulary relationships — four ways trick names can relate ───────
        Replaces the prior #compression-vs-alternate-derivation subsection
        and the standalone #symbolic-compression-flow mobius example, which
        fold into the new structure. Both anchors preserved (on the h3 and
        on the Structural compression h4) for inbound deep-links from
        external references.

        Authored 2026-05-25 per curator proposal: four relationship types
        (pure alias / structural compression / equivalent derivation /
        ontology relationship) explained with concrete movement-centered
        examples. Movement-language pedagogy, not academic ontology;
        avoids parser/AST terminology. Worked examples (flurry +
        witchdoctor) fold into Equivalent derivations subsection. }}
    <h3 class="section-heading" id="vocabulary-relationships">Vocabulary relationships &mdash; four ways trick names can relate</h3>
    {{! Preserve legacy anchor for deep-links; the prior subsection lived here. }}
    <a id="compression-vs-alternate-derivation"></a>
    <p>
      Freestyle vocabulary doesn&rsquo;t behave like ordinary
      dictionary words. The same trick may go by several names, and a
      single name may package a longer movement formula or admit
      alternate derivational routes. When a trick page shows a
      <strong>&equiv;</strong> reading (line 1), that reading is an
      <strong>interpretation</strong>, and the platform&rsquo;s
      <strong>interpretation doctrine</strong> is one rule: an interpretation
      is <em>descriptive, never a recipe</em>. It tells you what a trick can be
      read as; it does not hand you something to apply to other tricks.
    </p>
    <p>
      The boundary older vocabularies lost: <strong>a historical derivation is
      not a productive modifier.</strong>
      <a href="/freestyle/tricks/eggbeater">eggbeater</a> &equiv; atomic legover
      <span class="glossary-flagship-marker" title="Flagship: a historical reading is descriptive, not a productive operator">&#9733;</span>
      is two vocabularies describing one movement &mdash; it does <em>not</em>
      make &ldquo;eggbeater&rdquo; an operator you can apply (there is no
      &ldquo;eggbeater-ing&rdquo; another base). A genuine
      <a href="#section-modifiers">modifier ecosystem</a> (pixie, ducking) is
      the opposite: it <em>does</em> apply across many bases. A reading says
      what a trick <em>is equivalent to</em>; a modifier says what you can
      <em>do to</em> a base.
    </p>
    <p>
      Readings also arrive by different routes, and the route is worth knowing:
      an <strong>editorial equivalence</strong> (smear &equiv; pixie mirage), a
      <strong>historical derivation</strong> (eggbeater &equiv; atomic legover),
      a <strong>compositional descent</strong>
      (<a href="/freestyle/tricks/drifter">drifter</a> &equiv; miraging clipper
      <span class="glossary-flagship-marker" title="Flagship: a named structure built from canonical tricks — a compositional descendant, not a primitive family">&#9733;</span>,
      a named structure built from canonical tricks), a
      <strong>structural parse</strong> (the reading the notation itself yields),
      or a <strong>policy-dependent</strong> reading (one that holds only under a
      curator ruling). None of these is a productive modifier, and
      <strong>an interpretation is not always settled</strong>: some
      &equiv; readings are ratified structure, others are observational or
      ruling-dependent and may change. Four kinds of relationship recur often
      enough to name separately.
    </p>

    <h4 class="glossary-equivalence-worked-heading">1. Pure aliases &mdash; different names, same trick</h4>
    <p>
      The simplest case. The same operational structure carries
      multiple names, usually for historical reasons. Before the word
      <em>quantum</em> entered the vocabulary, players said <em>toe</em>
      for the same set of compounds; the curator pt2 ruling retired
      the older naming.
    </p>
    <ul class="glossary-equivalence-worked-example">
      <li><strong>toe blur</strong> &equiv; <a href="/freestyle/tricks/quantum-mirage">quantum mirage</a></li>
      <li><strong>toe blizzard</strong> &equiv; <a href="/freestyle/tricks/quantum-illusion">quantum illusion</a></li>
      <li><strong>toe ripwalk</strong> &equiv; quantum butterfly</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Aliases don&rsquo;t expose movement structure. They&rsquo;re
      naming, not composition. The two names refer to the same
      physical sequence.
    </p>

    {{! Preserve legacy anchor for deep-links to the mobius compression flow. }}
    <h4 class="glossary-equivalence-worked-heading" id="symbolic-compression-flow">2. Structural compression &mdash; names that encode composition</h4>
    <p>
      A trick name can compress a longer compositional reading into a
      single word. As freestyle vocabulary evolved, many commonly
      repeated compositions acquired compressed names that eventually
      became more familiar than their expanded structural readings
      &mdash; the short name is the everyday speech form; the
      expansion reveals how the trick is built from operators and
      bases.
    </p>
    <ul class="glossary-equivalence-worked-example">
      <li><strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/smear">smear</a></strong> &equiv; pixie mirage</li>
      <li><strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/ripwalk">ripwalk</a></strong> <span class="glossary-flagship-marker" title="Flagship teaching example: clean atom-level structural compression">&#9733;</span> &equiv; stepping butterfly</li>
      <li><strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/atom-smasher">atom smasher</a></strong> &equiv; atomic mirage</li>
      <li><strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/eggbeater">eggbeater</a></strong> &equiv; atomic legover</li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/mobius">mobius</a></strong> <span class="glossary-flagship-marker" title="Flagship teaching example: multi-depth compression ladder">&#9733;</span>
        &equiv; gyro torque
        &equiv; spinning same-side torque
        &equiv; spinning miraging same-side osis
        <em>(a compression ladder &mdash; same structure at four reading depths)</em>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Unlike aliases, these names <em>are</em> structural. Reading
      <em>ripwalk</em> as <em>stepping butterfly</em> makes the
      move&rsquo;s ancestry legible. A compressed name can sit at
      multiple expansion depths; mobius walks shallow-to-deep through
      four readings of the same trick, and the deepest reading is
      where the wow-moment lands &mdash; &ldquo;oh, these are
      compositional transformations.&rdquo; For a step-by-step
      walkthrough of how operators stack and how ADD totals are
      derived, see
      <a href="/freestyle/add-analysis">ADD Accounting &amp; Analysis</a>.
    </p>

    <h4 class="glossary-equivalence-worked-heading">3. Equivalent derivations &mdash; multiple valid paths</h4>
    <p>
      Some tricks admit more than one structural reading &mdash;
      different operator compositions that arrive at the same trick
      with the same ADD. Both paths are pedagogically live; neither is
      wrong.
    </p>
    <ul class="glossary-equivalence-worked-example">
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/flurry">flurry</a></strong> <span class="glossary-flagship-marker" title="Flagship teaching example: two valid derivations of the same trick">&#9733;</span>
        &equiv; <em>barraging legover</em>
        <span class="text-muted">(barraging(+2) + legover(2) = 4 ADD)</span>
        &equiv; <em>paradox + paradox legover</em>
        <span class="text-muted">(paradox(+1) + paradox-legover(3) = 4 ADD)</span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/witchdoctor">witchdoctor</a></strong>
        &equiv; <em><a href="/freestyle/tricks/atom-smasher">atom-smasher</a> + symposium</em>
        <span class="text-muted">(atom-smasher(4) + symposium(+1) = 5 ADD; current canonical)</span>
        &equiv; <em>atomic symposium mirage</em>
        <span class="text-muted">(historical reading, preserved as context)</span>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      When trick-detail pages show an &ldquo;Alternate
      derivations&rdquo; panel, this is what they&rsquo;re showing
      &mdash; structurally distinct routes through the movement
      language that converge on the same trick.
      <a href="/freestyle/tricks/flurry">See flurry &rarr;</a>
      <a href="/freestyle/tricks/witchdoctor">See witchdoctor &rarr;</a>
    </p>
    <p>
      Some equivalent derivations survive primarily as
      <strong>historical readings</strong> &mdash; older community
      language the trick was originally taught in, preserved even
      after a different canonical decomposition becomes preferred.
      Witchdoctor&rsquo;s <em>atomic symposium mirage</em> reading,
      the <em>toe</em>-prefixed naming retired by the curator pt2
      ruling (toe blur, toe blizzard, toe ripwalk), and several
      barrage-family decompositions all sit here. The historical
      reading is kept because it keeps older community language
      navigable, not because it&rsquo;s a competing claim against the
      current canonical.
    </p>

    <h4 class="glossary-equivalence-worked-heading">4. Ontology relationships &mdash; family ancestry and transformations</h4>
    <p>
      Beyond compression and equivalence, tricks relate by ancestry
      &mdash; a base trick anchors a family of related compounds that
      share structural DNA, and modifiers transform one trick into
      another along well-worn paths.
    </p>
    <ul class="glossary-equivalence-worked-example">
      <li>The <strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/butterfly">butterfly family</a></strong> anchors a walking progression (butterfly &rarr; ducking butterfly &rarr; spinning butterfly &rarr; &hellip;) where each step swaps or adds one operator.</li>
      <li>The <strong>legover family</strong> &mdash; <a href="/freestyle/tricks/legover">legover</a>, <a href="/freestyle/tricks/double-leg-over">double-leg-over</a>, <a href="/freestyle/tricks/eggbeater">eggbeater</a>, <a href="/freestyle/tricks/schmoe">schmoe</a> &mdash; share the same body event (leg over the bag) under different setup vehicles.</li>
      <li>The <strong>whirl family</strong> &mdash; <a href="/freestyle/tricks/whirl">whirl</a>, <a href="/freestyle/tricks/rev-whirl">rev-whirl</a>, <a href="/freestyle/tricks/gyro-whirl">gyro-whirl</a>, <a href="/freestyle/tricks/spinning-whirl">spinning-whirl</a>, <a href="/freestyle/tricks/paradox-whirl">paradox-whirl</a> &mdash; share the same rotational dex with different prefixes.</li>
      <li><strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/eclipse">eclipse</a> &rarr; <a href="/freestyle/tricks/hop-over">hop-over</a></strong> &mdash; eclipse is the airborne evolution of hop-over&rsquo;s grounded held-delay leg-over chassis.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      These aren&rsquo;t aliases (different names refer to different
      tricks) and they aren&rsquo;t compression (the family member is
      a distinct trick, not just a renaming). They&rsquo;re
      transformational: one trick is reachable from another by
      applying a structural modifier &mdash; add a body event, add a
      rotation, lift airborne.
    </p>

    <table class="glossary-equivalence-distinctions">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Relationship</th><th>Same trick?</th><th>Same structure?</th><th>What it asserts</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Pure alias</td><td>yes</td><td>yes</td><td>different name, identical sequence</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Structural compression</td><td>yes</td><td>yes (compressed)</td><td>the short name packages a compositional formula</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Equivalent derivation</td><td>yes</td><td>different structural reading/path (movement converges; derivation differs)</td><td>different operator paths arrive at the same trick &amp; ADD</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Ontology relationship</td><td>no (distinct trick)</td><td>related</td><td>linked by family ancestry or structural transformation</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>
      Advanced freestyle names can sound compressed, cryptic, or seem
      to admit multiple interpretations because the notation system
      isn&rsquo;t just labeling tricks &mdash; it&rsquo;s describing
      relationships between movement structures. Knowing which kind of
      relationship you&rsquo;re looking at tells you how to read the
      name: vocabulary, composition, derivation, or family.
    </p>

    <h4 class="glossary-equivalence-worked-heading" id="two-projections">Two projections of one move &mdash; and which name becomes official</h4>
    <p>
      Underneath all four relationships sits one idea. A trick has two ways of being
      named, and they are <strong>two projections of the same move</strong>, not two
      different things. One projection is the <strong>folk name</strong> the community
      speaks; the other is the <strong>structural decomposition</strong> &mdash; the
      operators and base the move is built from. Neither is more &ldquo;real&rdquo; than
      the other; they point at the same physical sequence from two directions.
    </p>
    <p>
      That is also how the platform decides two names mean the same trick: it compares
      the <strong>decomposed structure</strong>, not the spelling. Two names that look
      nothing alike are the same move when they decompose to the same operators and base
      &mdash; the match is on <em>structure</em>, never on <em>strings</em>.
    </p>
    <ul class="glossary-equivalence-worked-example">
      <li><strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/gauntlet">gauntlet</a></strong> &equiv; <em>stepping-ducking-paradox-torque</em> &mdash; a folk name and its structural reading, one 7-ADD move.</li>
      <li><strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/gyro-ducking-symposium-torque">gyro-ducking-symposium-torque</a></strong> &equiv; <em>alpine-big-apple</em> &mdash; a structural name and its folk reading, one 7-ADD move.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Which projection becomes the <strong>canonical</strong> (displayed) name is decided
      by which one the community actually uses &mdash; and it goes both ways. For
      <em>gauntlet</em> the folk name won, and the structural reading rides along as the
      alias; for <em>gyro-ducking-symposium-torque</em> the structural name won, and
      <em>alpine-big-apple</em> is the alias. The other projection is never discarded
      &mdash; it stays attached so either name still finds the trick.
    </p>
    <p class="glossary-section-next">Next &mdash; the <a href="#walking-family-progression">walking-family progression</a> below renders ontology relationships as a 7-step ladder off the butterfly base.</p>

    {{! ── Walking-family progression ────────────────────────────────────────
        Pedagogical pathway: seven named compounds that branch off the
        butterfly base, each adding or swapping one operator. Surfaces
        within §8 as a worked example of how a base trick anchors a
        family of compositionally-related tricks. Readings sourced from
        freestyleSymbolicEquivalences.ts. }}
    <h3 class="section-heading" id="walking-family-progression">Walking-family progression &mdash; a family worked example</h3>
    <p>
      Seven canonical compounds, each branching off the butterfly base
      by adding or swapping one operator. Read top-to-bottom for a tour
      of how the butterfly family climbs the difficulty ladder.
    </p>
    <ol class="glossary-walking-family-progression">
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/butterfly">butterfly</a></strong>
        <span class="glossary-walking-family-formula"><span class="notation-token notation-core-family">butterfly</span> <em>(base, 3 ADD)</em></span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/ripwalk">ripwalk</a></strong>
        <span class="glossary-walking-family-formula">&equiv; <span class="notation-token notation-modifier">stepping</span> <span class="notation-token notation-core-family">butterfly</span> <em>(4 ADD)</em></span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/dimwalk">dimwalk</a></strong>
        <span class="glossary-walking-family-formula">&equiv; <span class="notation-token notation-set">pixie</span> <span class="notation-token notation-core-family">butterfly</span> <em>(4 ADD)</em></span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/sidewalk">sidewalk</a></strong>
        <span class="glossary-walking-family-formula">&equiv; <span class="notation-token notation-modifier">stepping</span> <span class="notation-token notation-directionality">near</span> <span class="notation-token notation-core-family">butterfly</span> <em>(4 ADD)</em></span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/dada-curve">dada-curve</a></strong>
        <span class="glossary-walking-family-formula">&equiv; <span class="notation-token notation-modifier">miraging</span> <span class="notation-token notation-directionality">far</span> <span class="notation-token notation-modifier">symposium</span> <span class="notation-token notation-core-family">butterfly</span> <em>(4 ADD)</em></span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/matador">matador</a></strong>
        <span class="glossary-walking-family-formula">&equiv; <span class="notation-token notation-set">nuclear</span> <span class="notation-token notation-core-family">butterfly</span> <em>(5 ADD)</em></span>
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong><a href="/freestyle/tricks/phoenix">phoenix</a></strong>
        <span class="glossary-walking-family-formula">&equiv; <span class="notation-token notation-set">pixie</span> <span class="notation-token notation-modifier">ducking</span> <span class="notation-token notation-core-family">butterfly</span> <em>(5 ADD)</em></span>
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p class="glossary-walking-family-note">
      One base, seven named branches. Each operator added is also defined
      in the Modifiers &amp; Operators section; each compound has its own
      detail page with related-trick navigation back to the family.
    </p>

