  </section>
  {{/if}}

  {{! ── Observational case study — inside-delay stationary-transition neighborhood ──
      Curator-authored embodied-movement comparison (wrap / walk-over / hop-over / eclipse).
      Observational layer: groups by player-felt movement envelope, NOT canonical family —
      all four keep their own trick_family. Must stay semantically compatible with the four
      trick detail pages: never contradicts their op_notation, ADD accounting, or family, and
      the eclipse +1 mechanism renders as an explicitly open reading (commonly read as
      symposium; decomposition unsettled). If a detail page's canonical doctrine changes,
      update this section in lockstep. }}
  <section class="content-section glossary-connective-section" id="inside-clipper-neighborhood">
    <h2 class="section-heading">
      Case study: the inside-delay stationary-transition neighborhood
      <span class="symbolic-layer-badge" title="Observational movement-neighborhood lens — supplementary; does not change canonical classifications">observational</span>
    </h2>
    <p class="section-intro">
      Wrap, walk-over / step-over, hop-over, and eclipse are <em>embodied cousins</em>:
      they share a distinctive <strong>inside-delay stationary transition</strong>, in which
      the support-side body moves around a relatively stationary bag rather than sending the
      bag through space. To a newer player they look nearly identical &mdash; yet they earn
      their difficulty in fundamentally different ways. That tension is the lesson:
      <strong>ADD is not a pure difficulty metric, and embodied movement is its own axis</strong>.
    </p>
    <div class="glossary-add-weight-table-wrap">
      <table class="glossary-add-weight-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Trick</th><th>Dominant mechanism</th><th>ADD logic</th><th>Observational feel</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><a href="/freestyle/tricks/wrap">Wrap</a></td><td>dexterity</td><td>stall + dex</td><td>compact dex around a stationary bag</td></tr>
          <tr><td><a href="/freestyle/tricks/walk-over">Walk-over</a> / Step-over</td><td>dexterity</td><td>stall + dex</td><td>stepping body-over motion</td></tr>
          <tr><td><a href="/freestyle/tricks/hop-over">Hop-over</a></td><td>body</td><td>stall + body</td><td>full-body transition around the bag</td></tr>
          <tr><td><a href="/freestyle/tricks/eclipse">Eclipse</a></td><td>extended hop-over topology</td><td>hop-over + additional commitment</td><td>symposium-like escalation of hop-over mechanics</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p class="glossary-note">
      <strong>Why it matters.</strong> Wrap and walk-over take their second ADD from
      <em>dexterity</em>; hop-over takes its from <em>body motion</em> &mdash; visually similar
      tricks, different mechanisms. Hop-over is widely felt as harder than the dex-based 2-ADD
      variants despite the identical ADD, a clean example of ADD diverging from practical difficulty.
    </p>
    <p class="glossary-note">
      <strong>Eclipse.</strong> Eclipse occupies the same movement neighborhood as hop-over,
      adding an additional commitment layer (commonly interpreted as symposium / body commitment),
      though the precise decomposition remains <strong>doctrinally unsettled</strong>. The parser
      notation can be technically accurate while still not expressing this embodied relationship
      &mdash; the two readings coexist. See <a href="#tracking-vs-canonization">Tracking is not
      canonization</a>.
    </p>
    <p class="symbolic-layer-footer symbolic-layer-footer--glossary">
      Observational movement-neighborhood lens. Grouping is by player-felt movement envelope;
      the canonical family classifications (wrap, walk-over, hop-over, and eclipse each anchor
      their own family) are unchanged.
    </p>
  </section>

  {{! ── Advanced Reference Concepts — the publication-state vocabulary,
      relocated here (Phase E) from the glossary opening. It is reference
      machinery, not onboarding; the `how-to-read` anchor is preserved for
      inbound deep-links. }}
  <section class="content-section" id="section-advanced-reference">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Advanced Reference Concepts</h2>
    <p>
      The sections above use a small set of reference distinctions to mark
      what kind of claim each entry makes. They matter for deep reference and
      curation work &mdash; a first read of the glossary does not need them.
    </p>

    <h3 class="section-heading" id="primitives-and-compounds">Primitives and compounds</h3>
    <p>
      Two kinds of trick coexist in the freestyle dictionary, and the
      glossary, trick-detail surfaces, and ontology tooling all branch on
      the distinction.
    </p>
    <p>
      A <strong>foundational primitive</strong> &mdash; also called a
      <em>core atom</em> or simply an <em>atom</em> &mdash; is an irreducible
      movement. The platform treats it as a single unit rather than as a
      composition of smaller parts. The twelve core atoms are toe-stall,
      clipper-stall, around-the-world, orbit, legover, mirage, pickup,
      illusion, butterfly, osis, whirl, and swirl. Each carries an internal
      structural reading (xbody + dex + stall, for instance) that names the
      components of the motion, but the trick itself is the floor of the
      system: there is no shallower trick that the atom decomposes into.
    </p>
    <p>
      A <strong>compound</strong> &mdash; also called a
      <em>compositional structure</em> &mdash; is a trick built by applying
      modifiers, operators, or composition rules to one or more atoms.
      Paradox-mirage, atomsmasher, <a href="/freestyle/tricks/mobius">mobius</a>, <a href="/freestyle/tricks/blur">blur</a>, and baroque are all
      compounds. Compound tricks can be read as decomposition chains, may
      have multiple equivalence paths to the same reading, and surface
      those alternate derivations in the trick-detail
      &ldquo;Alternate derivations&rdquo; panel.
    </p>
    <p>
      The distinction matters in two places:
    </p>
    <dl class="glossary-primitives-compounds">
      <dt>Equivalence and compression analysis applies to compounds, not primitives.</dt>
      <dd>
        When a compound has more than one structurally-valid decomposition,
        the trick-detail page surfaces both readings as alternate
        derivations. Atoms intentionally omit this layer &mdash; they are
        the substrate the compositions are built from, not themselves
        further compressible.
      </dd>
      <dt>Decomposition is a structural claim, not a difficulty claim.</dt>
      <dd>
        Primitive vs compound is about ontology, not difficulty or scoring.
        Some atoms are mechanically demanding; some compounds are easier
        than the atoms they are built on. ADD values are independent of
        the distinction &mdash; atoms span 1&ndash;3 ADD, compounds span 2
        to 8+ ADD, and primitive-vs-compound tracks movement structure,
        not scored complexity.
      </dd>
    </dl>
    <p class="detail-muted">
      The same primitive/compound distinction applies to modifiers and
      operators. Stepping, paradox, atomic, and the other named modifiers
      are primitive operators; blurry (= stepping paradox) and the other
      operator-compositions are compound operators. The doctrine is the
      same in either case &mdash; primitives compose, compounds decompose.
    </p>

    <h3 class="section-heading" id="how-to-read">How to read this glossary</h3>
    <p>
      The glossary mixes several kinds of claim. Canonical material is
      authoritative; supplementary layers (observational, doctrine,
      historical) surface alongside it with explicit labels. Knowing the
      distinction lets a reader scan any section and know what kind of
      claim a given entry makes.
    </p>
    <dl class="glossary-publication-states">
      <dt>Canonical</dt>
      <dd>Community-sanctioned; single-valued; authoritative. Default text style, no badge. Lives in the trick dictionary and in the family cards.</dd>
      <dt>Observational</dt>
      <dd>Curator-derived movement-neighborhood lens. Supplements canonical without overriding it. Marked with an <em>observational</em> badge; lives in the Family &amp; Topology Concepts section and in expandable panels on family cards.</dd>
      <dt>Doctrine-sensitive</dt>
      <dd>A reading governed by a published doctrine (e.g. rotational continuity). The canonical ADD or decomposition holds; the doctrine explains <em>why</em>.</dd>
      <dt>Historical</dt>
      <dd>An older or community interpretation preserved as context, not as a competing claim. Lives in the Historical Terms section and inside trick-detail &ldquo;Alternate derivations&rdquo; panels.</dd>
      <dt>Alternate derivation (equivalence topology)</dt>
      <dd>A different structural route to the same trick, reaching the same ADD. Both readings are pedagogically live. Lives in the Symbolic Composition section and in trick-detail panels.</dd>
      <dt>Pending</dt>
      <dd>Curator-confirm-pending; not yet ratified. Surfaces with an <em>advanced</em> badge or, on dictionary cards, a &ldquo;decomposition under review&rdquo; pill. Never claimed as canonical.</dd>
    </dl>
    <p class="detail-muted">
      <strong>The settled/pending boundary is now well-defined.</strong> The
      modifier weights, the atomic / quantum X-Dex trigger, and the
      named-compound decompositions are <strong>ratified</strong>; the pending
      set is small &mdash; chiefly the counting-frame doctrine (how the
      <code>[PDX]</code> flag is tallied) and a few source-divergence cases where
      an external corpus disagrees with the IFPA-derived value. Anything still
      open renders with a pending state above and is never presented as final.
    </p>
    <p class="detail-muted">
      The shortest readable form of a trick name is the one the community
      uses; deeper readings remain available for readers who want to see the
      structure. Multiple readings often coexist legitimately. The glossary
      preserves all of them and marks which kind each one is.
    </p>

    <h3 class="section-heading" id="tracking-vs-canonization">Tracking is not canonization</h3>
    <p>
      The platform records more names than it endorses, on purpose.
      <strong>Documentation is not canonization.</strong> A name can be seen in
      the corpus and <strong>tracked</strong> for completeness, surfaced as an
      <strong>observational</strong> reading, or left <strong>unresolved</strong>
      while its structure is still open &mdash; none of which makes it a
      <strong>canonical</strong> trick. A name moves toward canonical only by
      being <strong>promoted</strong> after a ruling. Recording a name is
      evidence it exists in the culture, not a claim that it is settled
      structure.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section" id="section-media-claim-scope">
    <h2 class="section-heading">
      What a video can and can&rsquo;t tell you
      <span class="glossary-tier-badge glossary-tier-badge--advanced">Advanced Reference</span>
    </h2>
    <p>
      Curated video is a <strong>teaching layer</strong>, not a structural one. A
      clip shows you how a move looks and feels &mdash; it does <em>not</em> settle
      that move&rsquo;s canonical structure, ADD, or family. Those live in the
      <a href="/freestyle/tricks">trick dictionary</a> and its decompositions; a
      video is evidence the move is performed in the culture, never a ruling on how
      it decomposes.
    </p>
    <p>
      Each clip carries a <strong>claim scope</strong> &mdash; what kind of thing it
      asserts &mdash; shown as its media badge:
    </p>
    <dl class="glossary-publication-states">
      <dt>Tutorial</dt>
      <dd>Instructional: walks through how to perform the trick. The strongest teaching claim &mdash; the &ldquo;how-to&rdquo; for a move.</dd>
      <dt>Demonstration</dt>
      <dd>Shows the trick performed cleanly without a teaching breakdown &mdash; proof of the shape, not a lesson.</dd>
      <dt>Record</dt>
      <dd>A record-attempt clip with countable repetitions. Evidence of an achievement, not instruction; it never stands in for a tutorial.</dd>
    </dl>
    <p>
      The distinction matters because media <strong>teaches without resolving</strong>.
      A tutorial can clearly teach a move whose decomposition the dictionary still
      lists as open (see <a href="#tracking-vs-canonization">Tracking is not
      canonization</a>): the clip shows the movement; it does not close the
      structural question, and it never overrides the dictionary&rsquo;s canonical
      ADD or family.
    </p>
    <p>
      Where to find it: each trick page surfaces its own clips in a
      <strong>Reference Media</strong> block, and broader collections live in the
      <a href="/media">media galleries</a>.
    </p>
    <p class="glossary-note">
      A clip is tagged with the trick it shows. A future refinement may also mark a
      clip as <em>teaching a concept</em> or <em>covering components</em> of a move
      it doesn&rsquo;t directly name &mdash; an indirect-coverage idea reserved for
      later, not yet built.
    </p>
  </section>

