  <section class="content-section" id="section-sources">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Sources</h2>
    <p class="glossary-about-framing">
      This glossary records vocabulary the footbag community built informally over four decades. Authoritative trick-level definitions live in the <a href="/freestyle/tricks">Trick Dictionary</a>; the source families below contribute to the language documented here.
    </p>
    <ul class="glossary-sources-list">
      <li><strong><a href="https://www.footbag.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Footbag.org</a></strong> &mdash; the long-running community archive; trick lists, event records, and the foundational vocabulary catalogued there. See also the <a href="https://www.footbag.org/newmoves/list" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">historical per-trick move list</a>.</li>
      <li><strong>PassBackFootbag</strong> &mdash; conceptual tutorial series which introduced and formalised much of the modern compositional vocabulary (set / modifier / body operator framings).</li>
      <li><strong><a href="http://www-cs-students.stanford.edu/~blynn/footbag/moves.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Stanford shorthand</a></strong> &mdash; compact symbolic notation, an alternative encoding of the compositional grammar that exposes structural symmetries the spelled-out names sometimes obscure.</li>
      <li><strong><a href="https://www.footbagmoves.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">FootbagMoves</a></strong> &mdash; observational catalogue of named tricks, alternate names, and rotational variants; informs the symbolic-grammar layer of this glossary.</li>
      <li><strong>AnzTrikz</strong> &mdash; Australian / New Zealand demonstration series; canonical references for many compound rotational variants.</li>
      <li><strong>Footbag Finland</strong> &mdash; Finnish freestyle demonstration footage; visual references for several dictionary entries.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="glossary-about-framing">
      The vocabulary documented here rests on decades of foundational work
      by many people. The project owes particular thanks to Ben Job, Steve
      Goldberg, Adrian Dick, Damian Coventry, Stuart MacFerson, Chris Holden,
      Red Husted, Matt Kemmer, and Ben Lynn &mdash; whose contributions to
      freestyle's notation, archives, and movement language have been
      indispensable to this glossary and the dictionary it supports.
    </p>
    <p class="detail-muted">
      Definitions integrate the above sources without quoting any single
      one verbatim; where a term carries a contested decomposition, the
      authoritative trick page surfaces the open question explicitly.
    </p>
  </section>

